[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a good (self-explanatory) name for the product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\times B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">l</span></span></span></span></span>?</p>\n<p>It feels wrong to call it a the ``Cartesian product'', given that it's not a product in the categorical sense, but I don't know of any other name for it.</p>",
        "id": 234704908,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1618502707
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"278008\">Spencer Breiner</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/.24.24.5Ctimes.24.24.20in.20.24.24.5Cmathbf.7BRel.7D.24.24/near/234704908\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Is there a good (self-explanatory) name for the product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\times B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">l</span></span></span></span></span>?</p>\n<p>It feels wrong to call it a the ``Cartesian product'', given that it's not a product in the categorical sense, but I don't know of any other name for it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It is more like the bilinear tensor product of vector spaces.  In fact, in spans of finite sets seen through the equivalence with natural number matrices, it's the Kronecker product.<br>\nI would call it the multiplicative tensor product.</p>",
        "id": 234705723,
        "sender_full_name": "Cole Comfort",
        "timestamp": 1618502999
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You mean because <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">l</span></span></span></span></span>, as a model of linear logic, interprets both multiplicative conjunction and disjunction as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 234709321,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom Hirschowitz",
        "timestamp": 1618504249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I thought Cole was hinting at the fact that a relation is a matrix valued in the rig <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2 = \\{0,1\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>, so <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">l</span></span></span></span></span> is the category of free <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>-modules and module homomorphisms.  So we're doing linear algebra here, of a sort, and the product Spencer was talking about is the tensor product of free <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>-modules.   I'd say it deserves to be called the \"tensor product\".   You could even write it as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊗</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\otimes</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊗</span></span></span></span> to avoid fooling yourself into thinking it's the cartesian product in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">l</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 234709877,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1618504437
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But then in what sense does the tensor product of free <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>-modules deserve to be called \"multiplicative\"?</p>",
        "id": 234710669,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom Hirschowitz",
        "timestamp": 1618504701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It multiplies dimension</p>",
        "id": 234711077,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1618504868
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>At least for finite sets...</p>",
        "id": 234711150,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1618504894
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When you're taking the tensor product of modules (e.g. vector spaces) you don't say \"multiplicative\" tensor product: that's implicit in the symbol <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊗</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\otimes</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊗</span></span></span></span>.   But when we do abstract monoidal category theory we use <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊗</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\otimes</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊗</span></span></span></span> to mean any monoidal structure and then sometimes you feel the need to pound your fist on the table and emphasize it when you have a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊗</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\otimes</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊗</span></span></span></span> that's <em>really really</em> a tensor product in the classic sense of module theory.</p>",
        "id": 234711795,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1618505152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's also multiplicative in the sense that it distributes over finite coproducts (which is not unrelated to the points raised earlier of course).</p>",
        "id": 234713231,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1618505623
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's a lot of answers! Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276037\">@Jade Master</span> , <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> , <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276480\">@Reid Barton</span> , <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277391\">@Cole Comfort</span>.</p>",
        "id": 234745253,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom Hirschowitz",
        "timestamp": 1618517746
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yw</p>",
        "id": 234757429,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1618522129
    }
